{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>I am involved with teaching of 3 modules at the <a href=\"https://www.eng.ox.ac.uk/\">Engineering Science Department</a> of the <a href=\"http://www.ox.ac.uk/\">University of Oxford</a>. </p>\n<h2 id=\"b8-materials\"><a href=\"#b8-materials\" aria-label=\"b8 materials permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>B8 Materials</h2>\n<p>In this module, students learn about 4 of the most relevant materials in engineering design: metals, ceramics, polymers and composites.</p>\n<h2 id=\"b5-solid-mechanics\"><a href=\"#b5-solid-mechanics\" aria-label=\"b5 solid mechanics permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>B5 Solid Mechanics</h2>\n<p>In this module students study elasticity. In particular, I have led the practical demonstration and implemented the section of analysis of strains with digital image correlation analysis, used since 2016.</p>\n<h2 id=\"bx-introduction-to-fem\"><a href=\"#bx-introduction-to-fem\" aria-label=\"bx introduction to fem permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>BX Introduction to FEM</h2>\n<p>In the laboratory session students are given a design problem that they have to solve using the FEA module of SolidWorks.</p>","timeToRead":1,"excerpt":"I am involved with teaching of 3 modules at the  Engineering Science Department  of the  University of Oxford .  B8 Materials In this moduleâ€¦","frontmatter":{"title":"Teaching","template":"page"},"fields":{"nextTitle":"Learning in Public","nextSlug":"/learn/","prevTitle":"About me","prevSlug":"/me/","slug":"/teaching/","date":null}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/teaching/"}}